From: Trung Lê <8@tle.id.au>
Subject: dtprintinfo: install its app-defaults so help/About pane is white

Print Manager's (dtprintinfo) Help and "About" dialogs render their text in a
DtHelpDialog DisplayArea that should have a white background -- the printed-page
look every CDE help viewer uses (e.g. dtpad). Instead it inherits the desktop
palette color. SourceForge ticket #197.

The white DisplayArea override lives in the shared Dt resources (Dt.ad ->
app-defaults/<lang>/Dt) and is pulled into each app via "#include \"Dt\"" at the
top of that app's app-defaults file. dtpad's app-defaults does this; so does the
dtprintinfo source app-defaults (programs/dtprintinfo/Dtprintinfo, which is just
a header plus #include "Dt").

The bug: nothing ever builds or installs that Dtprintinfo file. The app-defaults
build list in programs/localized/templates/app-defaults.am omits Dtprintinfo, so
no app-defaults/<lang>/Dtprintinfo is produced. At runtime dtprintinfo (app class
"Dtprintinfo") therefore loads no app-defaults at all, never #includes "Dt", and
its help DisplayArea falls back to the palette *background.

This was misdiagnosed upstream as an XmDialogShell-vs-TransientShell resource
scoping problem in Dt.ad. It is not: dtprintinfo's help dialog is wrapped in an
XmDialogShell exactly like dtpad's (verified by building the widget tree), and
the existing Dt.ad rules match it fine once they are actually loaded.

Fix: wire Dtprintinfo into the app-defaults build like every other app -- add it
to BUILT_SOURCES, add the merge rule, and add a (string-free) Dtprintinfo.tmsg
for each shipped locale. The merged file keeps the #include "Dt", which Xrm
expands at load time, so dtprintinfo picks up the white help DisplayArea.

diff --git a/programs/localized/C/app-defaults/Dtprintinfo.tmsg b/programs/localized/C/app-defaults/Dtprintinfo.tmsg
new file mode 100644
index 000000000..d714db917
--- /dev/null
+++ b/programs/localized/C/app-defaults/Dtprintinfo.tmsg
@@ -0,0 +1,6 @@
+$ Dtprintinfo.tmsg
+$ The Dtprintinfo app-defaults file has no translatable strings: it only
+$ does #include "Dt" so Print Manager inherits the shared Dt resources
+$ (notably the white help DisplayArea background). This message file exists
+$ so the build produces and installs a Dtprintinfo app-defaults at all.
+$set 1
